tr:abstractText>&lt;p>The fellowship builds on the fellow?s PhD research which investigated the ways in which older adults (defined here as aged 65 and above) live with long term pain. Such pain is experienced by around 62 per cent of older people in the community and is associated with poor quality of life. However, older adult often do not seek help for long term pain. Both quantitative (a postal survey) and qualitative (face to face interviews) research methods were used to explore the views and experiences of older adults.&lt;br />&lt;br />The findings suggest that older adults talk about adjusting to long term pain in terms of ?acceptance?, which is informed by ideas around what is ?normal? in older age and by experiences of healthcare services given that pain is often hard to treat. Accepting pain was associated with use of some specific strategies to manage pain, and the research highlighted areas of unmet need.&lt;br />&lt;br />The fellowship means that these findings can be shared with a wide audience, including health care professionals, academics and older adults themselves. The fellowship will also help to ensure the fellow?s continued contribution to health care research by providing time to undertake training, develop collaborations and proposals for new research.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-10-02</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-10-03</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>75704</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>'You accept it : what other choice is there?' : acceptance as a framework for understanding how older adults live with chronic pain</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, w